shows that “the only difference between the distance in $\mathcal{E}$ and $\rho_R$ is the exponential weight added on $[R,\infty)$.”

To prove the main theorem, we follow an energy/coercivity approach in weighted spaces: unlike black solitons (which are “a saddle point of energy with a simple negative eigenvalue in the linearized operator $\mathcal{L}_-$,” where “symmetry-induced constraints allow us to obtain coercivity … and … a constrained minimizer of energy”), “the kink is already a minimizer of energy,” and “the symmetry-induced constraints are sufficient to show coercivity of the quadratic part of the energy functional in $\mathcal{H}_R^1$.” However, “the anharmonic part of the energy functional is not positive definite unless … $R>0$ … is chosen from the condition $\phi(R) > \frac{\sqrt{2}}{\sqrt{3}}$,” and “partitioning of $\mathbb{R}$ into $(-\infty,R)$ and $(R,\infty)$ induces a negative eigenvalue in the corresponding linearized operators,” so one must choose “$R>0$ sufficiently large” to prove that the symmetry constraints yield coercivity. This coercivity/energy expansion is what “leads to the proof of the main theorem developed later,” together with local well-posedness in $\mathcal{E}$ (“a necessary ingredient to the orbital stability theory”).

