Its proof ``utilize[s] the $L^4(\Omega)$- and $L^8(\Omega)$-estimates for $v$ as well as $L^2(\Omega)$- and $L^4(\Omega)$-estimates for $v_z$,'' and the dissipative terms in these estimates are ``nicely consistent'' for handling the ``most difficult nonlinearity'' $w v_z$, using in particular the estimates
\begin{equation} \label{eq1: treatment of wv_z}
\begin{aligned}
	C \int_\Omega |v| |v_z|^{r-1} |\nabla_H v_z| &\le C \big\| |v| |v_z|^{\frac{r}2} \big\|_{L^2(\Omega)} \big\| |v_z|^{\frac{r}2 - 1}|\nabla_H v_z| \big\|_{L^2(\Omega)} \\
		&\le \frac1{10} \big\| |v|^{\frac{r}2 - 1} |\nabla v_z| \big\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2 + C \big\| |v| |v_z|^{\frac{r}2} \big\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2,
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation} \label{eq2: treatment of wv_z}
\begin{aligned}
	\big\| |v| |v_z|^2 \big\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2 &= \int_\Omega |v|^2 (v_z \cdot v_z) |v_z|^2 \\
		&= \underbrace{ - \int_\Omega \partial_z (|v|^2) \cdot \frac12 \partial_z (|v|^2) |v_z^2| }_{ \le 0 } - \int_\Omega |v|^2 (v \cdot \partial_z v_z) |v_z|^2 - \int_\Omega |v|^2 (v \cdot v_z) 2 (v_z \cdot \partial_z v_z) \\
		&\le 3 (|v|^3 |v_z|, |v_z| |\partial_z v_z|)_\Omega \\
		&\le \frac1{10} \big\| |v_z| |\partial_z v_z| \big\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2 + C \big\| |v|^3 |v_z| \big\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
The drawbacks of this approach are that it is ``not directly applicable to the Dirichlet BC case'' and that ``the bound depends on $t$.''

- In establishing the main theorem for the Dirichlet BC case, they ``overcome the first difficulty'' by switching to ``the $L^6(\Omega)$-estimate for $v$ and $L^3(\Omega)$-estimate for $v_z$ (instead of $L^8$- and $L^4$-estimates).''

- In establishing the main theorem for the Neumann BC case with a time-independent $H^1$ bound, they ``employ[] a similar strategy'' but now ``eliminate time dependency from the $H^1$-upper bound.'' The ``main issue'' is the treatment of ``lower order terms,'' for which ``a Poincar\'e-type inequality is a key ingredient,'' using for instance
\begin{equation} \label{eq: treatment of lower-order term}
\begin{aligned}
	&C (\|\nabla_H \tilde v\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2 + \|\nabla_H \tilde v\|_{L^2(\Omega)}) \|\tilde v\|_{L^q(\Omega)}^q + \frac{q - 2}{q^2} \big\| \nabla_H |\tilde v|^{\frac{q}2} \big\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2 \\
	\le \; &C \|\nabla_H \tilde v\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2 (\|\tilde v\|_{L^q(\Omega)}^q + 1) + \frac{q - 2}{q^2} \big\| \nabla_H |\tilde v|^{\frac{q}2} \big\|_{L^2(\Omega)}^2,
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
Consequently, they consider $L^4(\Omega)$- and $L^6(\Omega)$-estimates for $\tilde v = v - \bar v$ in place of $v$, using that $\|\tilde v\|_{L^2(\Omega)} \le h \|v_z\|_{L^2(\Omega)}$ (cf. \cite[(6.4)]{GGHHK2020}).

- The resulting bounds are then closed via a Gronwall inequality (recalled immediately after this discussion).

