The proof of the main theorem is described as an "immediate consequence of" the following two theorems.

\begin{theorem}[Algebraic classification theorem] \label{th:ordersAllBasisG}
  Suppose $\du=(d_1,d_2,d_3)$ is a list of positive integers, where any repeated term is odd. Let $R$ be the sphere-product $\Q$-algebra generated by $x_1, x_2, x_3$ in degrees $\du=(d_1,d_2,d_3)$. If $A$ is an order in $R$, then there exists a coefficient sequence $\cf$ for which $A \iso A(\cf, \du)$.
\end{theorem}

\begin{theorem}[Topological existence theorem]\label{thm_top_main}
Let $\underline{d}=(d_1,d_2,d_3)$ be a list of positive integers greater than $1$, and let $\mathfrak{c} : \mathcal{P}([3]) \to \N$ be a coefficient sequence. 
There exists a $CW$-complex $X(\cf,\du)$ such that $H^*(X(\cf,\du);\Z)\cong A(\cf,\du)$.
\end{theorem}

The algebraic classification theorem gives that for an order $A$ in the $3$-generated sphere-product $\mathbb{Q}$-algebra $R$ (with the hypothesis that any repeated degree is odd), there exists a coefficient sequence $\mathfrak c$ such that $A \cong A(\mathfrak c,\underline d)$ (i.e., $A$ is a weighted sphere-product ring). Then the topological existence theorem realizes any such $A(\mathfrak c,\underline d)$ (when $d_i>1$) by a $CW$-complex $X(\mathfrak c,\underline d)$ with $H^*(X(\mathfrak c,\underline d);\mathbb Z)\cong A(\mathfrak c,\underline d)$. Combining these, one obtains a $CW$-complex $X_A$ with $H^*(X_A;\mathbb Z)\cong A$.

