\label{thm:intro-swap}
    The map $\swap$ gives bijections between the fully reduced web bases $\W_{\underline a}$ for all permutations of the boundary conditions $\underline{a}$.
\end{thm} ) and “thereby the main theorem, after some verifications for $r=2$ and $3$” carried out in Next it proves these results..

“The Fourier coefficients can be written as certain Eulerian integrals, so in establishing the main theorem, the proof is reduced to local computations at $g_{f}=1$.” The “most complicated part” is computing $a_{T}(E_{\ell},1)$ for anisotropic $T\in\mathbf{V}_{0}$, and the strategy is to “consider $\mathbf{V}_{0}$ as a quadratic space, with symmetric bilinear form $\tr_{E/\mathbb{Q}}\lrangle{\,}{\,}$.”

\begin{itemize}
\item (Finite places) “For a prime $p$, the $\Q_{p}$-component of $a_{T}(E_{\ell},1)$ is a combination of several quadratic Siegel series.” If $p$ is unramified in $E$, they “directly apply a result from \cite{KY2} on the Siegel series,” while if $p$ is ramified, they “prove a ramified version of this result.” In both cases the local factor is “the product of $(1-p^{n-2\ell-2})$ with $p^{(n-2\ell-1)v_{p}(\lrangle{T}{T})}Q_{T,p}(p^{\ell-\frac{n-1}{2}})$” (up to “some rational factor independent of $T$ when $p$ is ramified”), where $Q_{T,p}$ lies in “$\mathbb{Z}[X^{2}]+p^{1/2}X\mathbb{Z}[X^{2}]$” and satisfies “a certain functional equation.” Hence the product of finite components is “a rational multiple of $\zeta(2\ell-n+2)^{-1}\lrangle{T}{T}^{n-2\ell-1}$,” with denominator “bounded by an integer independent of $T$.”
\item (Archimedean place) The archimedean component is “the Fourier transform (on $\mathbf{V}_{0}(\mathbb{R})$, viewed as a quadratic space) of a complicated function $F_{0,\ell}$.” “Following the strategy of \cite{Po},” they compare $F_{0,\ell}$ to “the inverse Fourier transform of $\mathrm{Char}(\lrangle{T}{T}>0)\lrangle{T}{T}^{2\ell-n+1}\mathcal{W}_{T}(1)$,” and obtain that the archimedean contribution is “the product of $\pi^{2\ell-n+2}\lrangle{T}{T}^{2\ell-n+1}$ with a rational number independent of $T$.”
\end{itemize}

“Combining the two parts together,” they conclude that for anisotropic $T$, the coefficient $a_{T}(E_{\ell},1)$ “is a rational number with a uniformly bounded denominator,” yielding “the first rationality (or algebraicity) result for a family of quaternionic Eisenstein series.”

